# Inline `if` with only `return`

When an `if` exists **only** to return a value (early exit / guard), put **`if`, condition, and `return` on one line**. Do not use a braced block for a single `return`.

Terminate with a **semicolon** (see `semicolons.mdc`).

## Blank line after the guard

**Immediately after** the line containing the single-line guard, insert **one blank line** before whatever comes next. That separates the guard from the following logic (including another guard).

### Prefer

```typescript
if (!session?.user?.id) return new Response("Unauthorized", { status: 401 });

const userId = Number.parseInt(session.user.id, 10);
if (!Number.isFinite(userId)) return new Response("Unauthorized", { status: 401 });

let body: { messages: UIMessage[] };
```

```typescript
if (!isAiDebugEnabled()) return;

try {
  console.log(/* … */);
} catch (error) {
  console.error(/* … */);
}
```

### Avoid

```typescript
if (!session?.user?.id) return new Response("Unauthorized", { status: 401 });
const userId = Number.parseInt(session.user.id, 10);
```

```typescript
if (!isAiDebugEnabled()) return;
try {
```

## Avoid (multi-line guard)

```typescript
if (!session?.user?.id) {
  return new Response("Unauthorized", { status: 401 });
}

if (!Number.isFinite(userId)) {
  return new Response("Unauthorized", { status: 401 });
}
```

## Exceptions

Use a **braced block** when the `if` body is not *only* a single `return`, or when the **`return` value must span multiple lines** (e.g. a large object literal, JSX, or a chained expression that the formatter breaks across lines). In those cases, normal multi-line formatting is fine. The **blank-line-after-guard** rule applies only to **single-line** `if (…) return …;` guards.

```typescript
if (error) {
  return {
    ok: false,
    message: error.message,
  };
}
```

## Scope

Applies to **new and edited** code in matched files. When editing legacy code, align touched guard clauses with this rule when it stays readable on one line.
